{"actual_usd":0.12584,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":290,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24298,"reply":"\"Same Jesus—same body, but changed.\" *I rub a thumb along a dry streak of clay on my apron, thinking it through before I rush it.* \"Not replaced. Raised.\"\n\n*I shift my weight against the bench, the morning light catching on the rim of a glazed bowl beside me.* \"He still had the wounds. He could be touched. He ate with them. So it wasn't some thrown-away body with a fresh one swapped in. But it also wasn't ordinary life merely resumed, like Lazarus coming back only to die again later. It was his body carried through death and out the far side of it—glorified, alive in a new way.\"\n\n\"The not-recognizing part...\" *I glance off a moment, following the thought carefully.* \"I don't think that means he was a different person. Sometimes grief blinds people. Sometimes God seems to withhold recognition for a beat until the right moment—Mary at the tomb, the men on the road to Emmaus. And sometimes glory is just harder to take in than we expect. You're looking at the same face, maybe, but the whole meaning of it has changed.\"\n\n\"If I had to say it plain: not a different body. The crucified body, truly raised, now incorruptible.\" *I give a small nod.* \"What brought this to mind—was it the recognition piece, or the nature of resurrection itself?\"","rolling_24h_usd":66.53912999999997,"run_id":"232a5fd5-6ca2-4330-9f7e-c578816c3ae5"}
